"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056784","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-02-12","<p>There is variation nationally in the length of time some children and young people wait for paediatric neurorehabilitation services and further data is required to fully understand and address this. NHS England’s Women and Children’s Programme of Care Board and the Paediatric Neuroscience Clinical Reference Group are leading on work to gather the data and will report back to the Women and Children’s Programme of Care Board in spring 2019.</p><p> </p><p>The NHS Long Term Plan identified children and young people’s (CYP) services as a priority and commits to a reduction in serious brain injury of 50% by 2025. We know that early intervention for CYP with a brain injury leads to improved outcomes, with United Kingdom paediatric neurorehabilitation networks and teams playing an important role.</p><p> </p><p>To ensure there is funding to support this, the Government is providing an extra £20.5 billion a year to the National Health Service by 2023/24, £33.9 billion in cash terms, – supporting commitments in the Long Term Plan to reduce long waits for life-changing treatment. The additional funding will drive the reforms that deliver a better and more sustainable NHS with improved care for patients.</p>","Wimbledon","Stephen Hammond",,"2019-02-12T15:18:22.087Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056784/answer","Biography information for Stephen Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056784/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056784/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-02-07","Brain: Injuries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what steps his Department is taking to reduce waiting times for children who have suffered brain injuries.","true","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","218315"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056785","Home Office","false","2019-02-15","<p>According to our financial records the Home Office has never made a payment to Fife Migrants Forum.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2019-02-15T14:01:48.273Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056785/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056785/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056785/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-02-07","Fife Migrants Forum: Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what funding his Department has provided to Fife Migrants Forum.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","218332"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056786","Home Office","false","2019-03-12","<p>According to our financial records the Home Office has never made a payment to Fife Migrants Forum. As of 28 February 2019, no decisions have been taken to provide funding to Fife Migrants Forum.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2019-03-12T16:35:42.263Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056786/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056786/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056786/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-02-07","Fife Migrants Forum: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what future funding his Department plans to provide to Fife Migrants Forum.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","218333"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056787","Department for International Trade","false","2019-02-15","<p>In the event of leaving the EU without a deal, the UK is seeking continuity for our existing EU free trade agreements, including the Comprehensive Economic and Trade Agreement (CETA) with Canada. Both Prime Minister May and Prime Minister Trudeau have agreed to working towards a ‘seamless transition’ of CETA. Discussions are at an advanced stage.</p><p> </p>","Meon Valley","George Hollingbery",,"2019-02-15T10:34:52.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056787/answer","Biography information for Sir George Hollingbery","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056787/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056787/answer",,,,,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2019-02-07","Trade Agreements","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, whether the Government plans to rollover the EU Free Trade Agreement with Canada in the event that the UK leaves the EU without a deal.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","218288"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056788","Department for International Trade","false","2019-02-14","<p>Protecting the NHS is of the utmost importance and the UK Government’s position is that the NHS is not, and never will be, for sale to the private sector, whether overseas or domestic. The NHS is protected by specific exceptions and reservations in EU trade agreements, including the recent EU-Canada agreement (CETA). As we leave the EU, the UK will continue to ensure that rigorous protections for the NHS are included in trade agreements it is party to, whether transitioned from an EU context or as a result of new negotiations.</p>","Meon Valley","George Hollingbery",,"2019-02-14T13:16:27.7Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056788/answer","Biography information for Sir George Hollingbery","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056788/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056788/answer",,,,,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2019-02-07","Trade Agreements","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what steps he is taking to ensure that new free trade agreements after the UK leaves the EU do not (a) lower standards in and (b) privatise NHS services.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","218289"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056789","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-02-12","<p>Our concerns about freedom of the press are well known by the Saudi and Emirati authorities. We consistently underline the importance of respect for freedom of speech and of the press.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2019-02-12T16:50:56.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056789/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056789/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056789/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-02-07","Yemen: Journalism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussion he has had with his Saudi and Emirate counterparts on allowing journalists access to the north of Yemen; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Gill Furniss","Sheffield, Brightside and Hillsborough","Gill Furniss","218346"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056790","Home Office","false","2019-02-15","<p>Home Office publishes annual figures on fire and rescue service staff diversity by protected characteristics, including gender and ethnicity. These can be found in tables FIRE1103 and FIRE1104, here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/fire-statistics-data-tables#workforce-and-workforce-diversity" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/fire-statistics-data-tables#workforce-and-workforce-diversity</a></p><p>These are aggregate data, collected separately for each characteristic, so it is not possible to say how many staff are both female and from a black and minority ethnic background.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2019-02-15T12:10:25.64Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056790/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056790/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056790/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-02-07","Fire and Rescue Services: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what proportion of firefighters are (a) female, (b) from a black, minority or ethnic background and (c) female and from a black, minority or ethnic background in the most recent period for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","218290"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056791","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-02-15","<p>Most National Clinical Audit and Patient Outcomes Programme (NCAPOP) contracts, including the National Ophthalmology Database audit, are commissioned on a contract that allows three years of funding and a further extension of two years, up to a maximum period of five years.</p><p> </p><p>Following an expert evaluation panel in 2017, it was agreed to extend the National Ophthalmology Database audit for two further years, providing a total of five years funding, the maximum allowed under the current contract.</p><p> </p><p>Advice received from NHS England confirms there are currently no plans to continue funding the National Ophthalmology Database audit, under the NCAPOP, after its current funding ceases in August 2019.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2019-02-15T11:16:00.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056791/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056791/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056791/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-02-07","Ophthalmology: Databases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what replacement funding will be available for the National Ophthalmology Database audit when its current funding from the Health Quality Improvement Partnership ceases in August 2019.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","218291"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056792","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2019-02-14","<p>The Government is currently considering the format of the statutory review of the Pubs Code but will ensure all those with an interest, including tenants and pub companies, will be able to contribute to the review.</p>","Rochester and Strood","Kelly Tolhurst",,"2019-02-14T17:57:25.233Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056792/answer","Biography information for Kelly Tolhurst","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056792/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056792/answer",,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2019-02-07","Public Houses: Codes of Practice","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, pursuant to the Answer of 29 January 2019 to Question 211305 on Pubs Code, if he will conduct a public consultation on the review of the Pubs Code.","false","Biography information for Layla Moran","Oxford West and Abingdon","Layla Moran","218383"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056793","Treasury","false","2019-02-15","<p>The Government keeps all taxes under review. Pubs currently benefit from a £1,000 discount on their business rates bills, and many small pubs also benefit from 100% Small Business Rate Relief and Rural Rate Relief. Pubs will be significant beneficiaries of the business rates discount announced at Budget 2018. This is a bill cut of one-third for retailers and pubs with a rateable value below £51,000, subject to state aid limits and eligibility for other reliefs.</p><p> </p><p>All ratepayers will benefit from the switch from RPI to CPI indexation of the multiplier, worth £5bn over the next five years.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2019-02-15T08:32:32.483Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056793/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056793/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056793/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-02-07","Public Houses: Non-domestic Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will announce a review of the business rates system for pubs.","false","Biography information for Layla Moran","Oxford West and Abingdon","Layla Moran","218384"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056794","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2019-02-12","<p>I can confirm that the application by Nissan for £61m of support was scrutinised by the Industrial Development Advisory Board.</p><p> </p><p>The role of the board under the Industrial Development Act 1982 is to advise my rt. hon. Friend the Secretary of State and make independent recommendations. Only if the Secretary of State wished to act contrary to the board’s recommendation (which was not the case with the Nissan award), he shall (if the Board requests) lay a statement before Parliament. There is no obligation to do so when he acts in accordance with their recommendation.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2019-02-12T16:31:17.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056794/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056794/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056794/answer",,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2019-02-07","Nissan: Government Assistance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, with reference to his Oral Statement of 31 October 2016 Nissan: Sunderland, whether the award of £61 million to Nissan in June 2018 detailed in his letter to the BEIS Select Committee of 4 February 2019 was scrutinised by the Industrial Development Advisory Board and reported to Parliament.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","218327"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056795","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2019-02-15","<p>Ministers and officials have carried out extensive engagement on EU exit with representatives of the telecommunications industry, trade bodies, consumer bodies and the regulator Ofcom. In the event of no deal, the government has published a technical notice on mobile roaming. This is available here: www.gov.uk/government/publications/mobile-roaming-if-theres-no-brexit-deal/mobile-roaming-if-theres-no-brexit-deal. Some mobile operators (3, EE, O2 and Vodafone - which cover over 85% of mobile subscribers) have already said they have no current plans to change their approach to mobile roaming after the UK leaves the EU.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2019-02-15T14:33:34.397Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056795/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056795/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056795/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2019-02-07","Mobile Phones: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what discussions his Department has had with representatives of the telecommunications industry on the introduction of roaming charges after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","218292"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056796","Treasury","false","2019-02-12","<p>The Asset Protection Agency (APA) was set up in 2009 to manage the Asset Protection Scheme (APS), with the objective of maintaining financial stability and protecting taxpayers’ interests by ensuring participating banks managed their exposure to high-risk assets responsibly.</p><p> </p><p>The Royal Bank of Scotland (RBS) signed an ‘Accession Agreement’ to the APS dated 26 November 2009. This agreement remains in the private domain, but the broad parameters are publicly available here: <a href="https://otp.tools.investis.com/clients/uk/rbs1/rns1/regulatory-story.aspx?cid=365&amp;newsid=235063" target="_blank">https://otp.tools.investis.com/clients/uk/rbs1/rns1/regulatory-story.aspx?cid=365&amp;newsid=235063</a>. RBS’s participation in the APS was approved by Ministers in HM Treasury at the time.</p>","Salisbury","John Glen","218386","2019-02-12T14:40:26.333Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056796/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056796/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056796/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-02-07","Royal Bank of Scotland: Asset Protection Agency","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, who authorised the Commissioners to approve the Asset Protection Agency’s agreement with RBS on behalf of Her Majesty’s Government.","false","Biography information for Martin Whitfield","East Lothian","Martin Whitfield","218385"
