"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1055951","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-02-11","<p>MHCLG supported the National Police Chiefs’ Council (NPCC) to create and populate a database of symbols of proscribed organisations for use by police forces. Information about the impact that these symbols and others have on community tensions has also been included.</p>","South Derbyshire","Mrs Heather Wheeler",,"2019-02-11T17:09:09.023Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1055951/answer","Biography information for Mrs Heather Wheeler","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1055951/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1055951/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-02-06","Antisemitism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, pursuant to Answer of 24 April to Question 136144 on Antisemitism, what progress his Department has made on creating a database of (a) symbols, (b) slogans and (c) flags that may be illegal as a result of their use to incite hatred.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","217670"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1055952","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-02-14","<p>NHS England has issued guidance around the commissioning of biological medicines and expects clinical commissioning groups (CCGs) to give due consideration to this guidance. The framework sets out the importance of developing local policies to support switching patients to biosimilars in line with best practice and where appropriate. The commissioning framework set out policy based on best practice but ultimately CCGs and hospital trusts are accountable for their own local decision making.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>All National Health Service organisations have a responsibility to encourage a shift in moving to shared decision making, and in ensuring that all patient consultations are done with a focus on shared decision making, and are happening at an individual healthcare professional/patient level.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England has also made clear that the decision to prescribe a biological medicine for an individual patient, whether an originator or biosimilar, or to change between the two, rests with the responsible prescriber in consultation with the patient, in line with the principles of shared decision making.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine","217620 ; 217621 ; 217623","2019-02-14T17:32:00.423Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1055952/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1055952/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1055952/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-02-06","Biosimilar Medicines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what steps his Department is taking to ensure that hospital trusts adhere to (a) shared decision-making principles and (b) patient consent guidance within NHS England's Commissioning framework for biological medicines (including biosimilar medicines) when implementing bio-similar medicine switching programmes.","false","Biography information for Chris Green","Bolton West","Chris Green","217619"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1055953","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-02-14","<p>NHS England has issued guidance around the commissioning of biological medicines and expects clinical commissioning groups (CCGs) to give due consideration to this guidance. The framework sets out the importance of developing local policies to support switching patients to biosimilars in line with best practice and where appropriate. The commissioning framework set out policy based on best practice but ultimately CCGs and hospital trusts are accountable for their own local decision making.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>All National Health Service organisations have a responsibility to encourage a shift in moving to shared decision making, and in ensuring that all patient consultations are done with a focus on shared decision making, and are happening at an individual healthcare professional/patient level.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England has also made clear that the decision to prescribe a biological medicine for an individual patient, whether an originator or biosimilar, or to change between the two, rests with the responsible prescriber in consultation with the patient, in line with the principles of shared decision making.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine","217619 ; 217621 ; 217623","2019-02-14T17:32:00.47Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1055953/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1055953/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1055953/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-02-06","Biosimilar Medicines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what steps are taken in cases where guidance within NHS England's Commissioning framework for biological medicines for biological medicines (including biosimilar medicines) is shown not to have been taken and patients are switched to a different medicine without their knowledge or consent.","false","Biography information for Chris Green","Bolton West","Chris Green","217620"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1055954","Ministry of Defence","false","2019-02-12","<p>In October 2018, a Joint Vision Statement was signed, reaffirming the continuing importance of close defence co-operation with Germany. This committed the UK to a combined river crossing capability with shared facilities in Minden. Elements of 23 Amphibious Engineer squadron, including some M3 rigs, are already located at Minden and will continue to grow until it is fully established in 2020.</p><p> </p><p>We do not routinely comment on specific locations for individual capabilities as to do so would compromise operational security, or would, or would be likely to, prejudice the capability, effectiveness or security of the Armed Forces.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster","217503","2019-02-12T16:47:45.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1055954/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1055954/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1055954/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2019-02-06","Army: Germany","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many M3 Amphibious Rigs are available at Ayrshire Barracks in Monchengladbach; when those M3 Amphibious Rigs will be transferred to the German Army barracks at Minden; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","217504"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1055955","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-02-14","<p>NHS England has issued guidance around the commissioning of biological medicines and expects clinical commissioning groups (CCGs) to give due consideration to this guidance. The framework sets out the importance of developing local policies to support switching patients to biosimilars in line with best practice and where appropriate. The commissioning framework set out policy based on best practice but ultimately CCGs and hospital trusts are accountable for their own local decision making.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>All National Health Service organisations have a responsibility to encourage a shift in moving to shared decision making, and in ensuring that all patient consultations are done with a focus on shared decision making, and are happening at an individual healthcare professional/patient level.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England has also made clear that the decision to prescribe a biological medicine for an individual patient, whether an originator or biosimilar, or to change between the two, rests with the responsible prescriber in consultation with the patient, in line with the principles of shared decision making.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine","217619 ; 217620 ; 217623","2019-02-14T17:32:00.53Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1055955/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1055955/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1055955/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-02-06","Biosimilar Medicines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what steps NHS England is taking to ensure that that hospital trusts across the NHS are following shared decision-making principles and patient consent guidance within NHS England's Commissioning framework for biological medicines (including biosimilar medicines) when implementing bio